</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/utuan00dorf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tuan00Dorf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 873<br> <font color=#E9D756>(11/26/01 2:56:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=38.topic&index=8>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Yea, he's pretty big...</span><hr size=1> Well, but you see there is still item camping in DAoC, you still wait for a mob and wait to get a specific item from him.  All DAoC tried to do, was make it easier, which I don't even agree with.<br>
<br>
In my eyes, daoc took the &quot;accomplishment&quot; part out of everything.  It was so awsome in Everquest to get new items after camping them.  But it daoc you don't feel that, because it didn't take that long (usually), and that item is going to be useless to you in a few levels because it will be grey.<br>
<br>
So, while it sounds all good that you can get new items quicker than EQ, I sure don't like it. <p>Tuan {Cupcakes} the Vicar</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uvendrix.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Vendrix</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 1137<br> <font color=#E9D756>(11/26/01 5:41:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=38.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Yea, he's pretty big...</span><hr size=1> <font color=fff00> In my eyes, daoc took the "accomplishment" part out of everything. It was so awsome in Everquest to get new items after camping them. But it daoc you don't feel that, because it didn't take that long (usually), and that item is going to be useless to you in a few levels because it will be grey.</font><br>
<br>
DaoC has it right in making the mundane magical items easy to obtain, either via quest or commonly spawning npc with a one-time-drop. Some things shouldn’t require you to spend hours on end, they just aren't worth it but sometimes you want them for neatness factor, resist, etc.<br>
<br>
When playing EQ, around the time my Necromancer was level 30ish, I read about what I perceived to be a kickass drop in Upper Guk – the Shimmering Orb. Did this item have uber stats? Not by a long shot, but it was cool as hell looking… and what's the point of playing if you don’t look good? Actually, this was way before that Stein quest went into the game, so off-hand options were somewhat limited.<br>
<br>
So I set out to camping the Scryer, I knew where he spawned so it was just a matter of time before he dropped the Chalupa. There I sat, killing everything on that platform for an entire day(I think I was home from work sick at the time). 10 hours and 4 Woven Grass Bracers later I was the proud owner of one less-than-l33t Shimmering Orb. I consider that to be a very mundane magical item, definitely not something worth 10 hours of someone’s time.<br>
<br>
I'm not saying daoc has it perfect, I'm really hating the one-time-drop level requirement bullshit, but they’re taking steps in the right direction.<br>
<br>
p.s. Dorfs still sux! <p><b>Vendrix</b><br>
<a href=http://www.dakor.net><font size=2>Da</a><a href=http://www.fatsex.com/tour>`</a><a href=http://www.dakor.net>Kor</font></a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/utuan00dorf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tuan00Dorf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 875<br> <font color=#E9D756>(11/26/01 1:31:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=38.topic&index=10>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Yea, he's pretty big...</span><hr size=1> Well I do agree Ven that some camps in EQ can turn into wayyy to long of them if you are unlucky.  But from another perspective, a lot of things in EQ that are camped are done for xp also.  So while people are spendng their hours getting so and so item, they are getting exp so not totally wasting their time.<br>
<br>
I think there is just some fine line between where camps become excessive, and I don't really think a majority of EQ camps are on the end of that spectrum (yes, there are a few that are almost outragous, but a majority are not).  While DAoC has done some new stuff in terms of camping, I don't see it any closer to the optimal, but just on the other side of that spectrum.<br>
<br>
Combine daoc camps with the &quot;fun/reward&quot; of EQ camps and you would have something good.<br>
<br>
I mean, in EQ I don't know about other people, maybe I'm just crazy, but I usually had fun camping items.  Even if it took a while, I was usually there with a friend, or even solo, and it was just fun doing that.  I just never really got that feeling in daoc.<br>
<br>
p.s. what's a dorf?<br>
 <p>Tuan {Cupcakes} the Vicar</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uarikel.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Arikel</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 1951<br> <font color=#E9D756>(11/26/01 11:33:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=38.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Yea, he's pretty big...</span><hr size=1> I think that perspectives on camping in DAoC vs. EQ depend on personal taste.  There are very few items that I view as worthy of being called accomplishments in EQ.  It's just some pixels that you sat on your ass for a long time to get, in my view.  I'd rather have fun running around roleplaying, doing interesting quests (I find the DAoC quest storylines much more interesting than most of EQ's, an exception being EQ's epic quests), and kicking monster ass with other people.  I think that if a sense of accomplishment is high on your list of things you want out of a game, DAoC may or may not appeal to you. <p>Ahry - hero of Gaoth an Iar, Percival server <BR>
